@node Ctrl "Controllers"

@{b}CONTROLLERS----------------------------@{ub}

Emerson Arcadia 2001:

The genuine consoles have four buttons on the console itself (START, A, B,
RESET). There are also two semi-detachable "hand controllers". Each of
these controllers has a "paddle" (analog-style joystick) and a "keypad" of
12, 14 or 16 buttons. Only the Dictionary program (and the MUSIC.BIN
homebrew example) make use of the extra buttons of the 16-button
controller.

Interton VC 4000:

The genuine consoles have three buttons on the console itself (START,
SELECT, RESET). There are also two semi-detachable "hand controllers".
Each of these controllers has a "paddle" (analog-style joystick) and a
"keypad" of 12 buttons.

The 14-button (MPT-03-style) keypad layout is arranged and named as
follows, the same as an MPT-03:

      2     2    You will observe that there are three buttons which all
      1  2  3    produce the same "scancode"; ie. they do the same thing;
      4  5  6    it is impossible for the guest machine (ie. the game)
      7  8  9    to differentiate between them.
     Cl  0 En

2:  2/Fire
Cl: Clear
En: Enter

Elektor TV Games Computer:

There are the following keys, and 2 paddles:

    .UC..   RCAS. WCAS. ..C..   ..D.. ..E.. ..F..
    START   BP1/2 .REG. ..8..   ..9.. ..A.. ..B..
    .LC..   .PC.. .MEM. ..4..   ..5.. ..6.. ..7..
    RESET   ..-.. ..+.. ..0..   ..1.. ..2.. ..3..

PIPBUG-based machines:

The emulator passes keyboard input to the game. Only keyboard is
supported. Remapping is not possible. The main Ami/WinArcadia window
must the active one. The notes below, about paddles, gamepads, etc., do
not apply to PIPBUG-based machines.
  AmiArcadia only: You cannot use "P" as a shortcut for pause/unpause,
nor Backspace as a shortcut for CPU tracing on/off, while in PIPBUG mode.
(Access to these via the menu and toolbar is still possible.)

@{b}Guest-Host Mapping@{ub}

This is the default mapping. You can change these key assignments by using
the {"Settings|Controllers|Redefine keys... command" link Sett}.

      F1: 'START'
      F2: 'A'     (Emerson Arcadia 2001)
      or 'SELECT' (Interton VC 4000)
      or 'UC'     (Elektor TV Games Computer)
      F3: 'B'     (Emerson Arcadia 2001)
      or 'LC'     (Elektor TV Games Computer)
      F4: 'RESET' (Elektor TV Games Computer only - RESET key)
      F5: 'RESET' (reset to game)
 Amiga-,: 'RESET' (Elektor TV Games Computer only - reset to monitor)

The F4 reset merely sets the appropriate bit in the key matrix
corresponding to the RESET button; it is up to the game to act on this.
  The F5 reset ("reset to game") merely causes the IAR (program counter)
to be reset to the start of the game.
  The "reset to monitor" merely causes the IAR to be reset to the start of
the monitor ROM (which is what happens when the real machine is reset).

    @{u}@{b}Left Player    Right Player    Right Player@{uu}@{ub}
      @{u}@{b}(both)       (AmiArcadia)    (WinArcadia)@{uu}@{ub}

         I             Up              Up
        \\|/            \\|/             \\|/
       J-+-L         Lt-+-Rt         Lt-+-Rt
        /|\\            /|\\             /|\\
         K             Dn              Dn

     a1 a2 a3        n( n) n/        nL n/ n*      Emerson/Elektor-style
      Q  W  E        n7 n8 n9        n7 n8 n9
      A  S  D        n4 n5 n6        n4 n5 n6
      Z  X  C        n1 n2 n3        n1 n2 n3

     a2    a2        n)    n)        n/    n/      MPT-03/Interton-style
     a1 a2 a3        n( n) n/        nL n/ n*
      Q  W  E        n7 n8 n9        n7 n8 n9
      A  S  D        n4 n5 n6        n4 n5 n6
      Z  X  C        n1 n2 n3        n1 n2 n3

        a2              n)              n/         Palladium-style
     a4  R  F        n* n- n+        n- n+ nE
     a1  V a3        n( nE n/        nL n. n*
      Q  W  E        n7 n8 n9        n7 n8 n9
      A  S  D        n4 n5 n6        n4 n5 n6
      Z  X  C        n1 n2 n3        n1 n2 n3

a:  alphanumeric
n:  numeric
NL: NumLock
nE: numeric ENTER
n.: numeric . (dot, full stop)

The @{"View|Controls... command" link View} is useful.

@{b}Using joysticks and gamepads@{ub}

The joystick/gamepad directions are mapped to the paddle directions as
you would expect.

                                        @{b}@{u}Arcadia/@{ub}@{uu}
    @{b}@{u}Gamepad button (joystick button)    Interton       Elektor@{uu}@{ub}
    Red (primary firebutton)            usually '2'    usually 'WCAS'/'E'
    Blue (secondary firebutton)         usually '1'    usually 'RCAS'/'D'
    Green (-)                           usually '3'    usually 'C'/'F'
    Yellow (-)                          usually '0'    usually '+'/'2'
    Reverse (-)                         A/SELECT       UC
    Forward (-)                         B/-            LC
    Play (-)                            START/START    START

    .UC..   RCAS. WCAS. ..C..   ..D.. ..E.. ..F..
    START   BP1/2 .REG. ..8..   ..9.. ..A.. ..B..
    .LC..   .PC.. .MEM. ..4..   ..5.. ..6.. ..7..
    RESET   ..-.. ..+.. ..0..   ..1.. ..2.. ..3..

AmiArcadia: By default, Amiga gameport '2' (the usual joystick/gamepad
port) controls the left player, and Amiga gameport '1' (the usual mouse
port) controls the right player.
  WinArcadia: By default, the first game input device controls the left
player, and the second game input device controls the right player.
@endnode

